COPD stands for Chronic Obstructive Pulmonary Disease.
The word Chronic means it wonâ€™t go away.The word Obstructive means partly blocked.
The word Pulmonary means in the lungs. The word Disease means sickness. COPD, a common preventable and treatable disease COPD, is characterised by persistent airflow limitation that is usually progressive and associated with an enhanced chronic inflammatory response in the airways and the lungs to noxious particles or gases. Exacerbations and comorbidities contribute to the overall severity in individual patients. (GOLD, 2014).

content.description: Find out more about symptoms of COPD
People with COPD have difficulties breathing, primarily due to the narrowing of their airways, this is called airflow obstruction.

content.content: Please remember to seek the advice of your doctor, GP or pharmacist regarding your lifestyle management. Your doctor or pharmacist is in the best position to provide you with the necessary advices on how to manage your lifestyle. Here are some advices to help you better manage your condition: 1.Keep your body strong and active. 2.Follow the instructions of your doctor when you take your medication(s). 3.Be sure you get influenza vaccine each year. 4.Be sure you get pneumococcal vaccine. 5.Eat healthy food. 6.Stop smoking: this is the first advice that you will get from your doctor or pharmacist if you are a current smoker. 7.Stay away from dusty places and where others are smoking to avoid the effects of second hand smoke. 8. Keep the air fresh and clean at home.

What is pulmonary rehabilitation? Pulmonary rehabilitation is defined as a multidisciplinary programme of care for patients with chronic respiratory impairment that is individually tailored and designed to optimise each patient's physical and social performance and autonomy. Pulmonary rehabilitation is recommended for all appropriate people with COPD including those who have had a recent hospitalisation for an acute exacerbation. Pulmonary rehabilitation is not suitable for patients who are unable to walk, have unstable angina or who have had a recent myocardial infraction.

content.content: Your diet and nutritional intake are very important when you have a disease like COPD. COPD can have an effect on your whole body. It is therefore important to eat a balanced and varied diet to help maintain your strength and fitness, as well as help your body fight infections. When you are feeling well and strong, healthy eating can keep you feeling this way. It is important to think about your weight. If you are very overweight your heart and lungs have to work harder to supply oxygen to your body. Likewise if you are too thin you are more at risk from infections. Body Mass Index (BMI) is a simple index of weight-for-height that is commonly used to classify underweight, overweight and obesity in adults.  BMI is your weight in kg divided by your height in metres squared. BMI = weight (kg)/ height2 (m2) For example, if your weight is 70kg and you are 1.75m tall, then your BMI is calculated as followed: BMI = 70 kg / (1.75*1.75) m2 = 70 / 3.06 = 22.9 kg/m2.
